<div class="container">
    <h1>The Client</h1>
    <p>In web communication, a <strong>client</strong> is the application or device that initiates a request to a server. The client can be a web browser, mobile app, or any software that interacts with a server to access data or services.</p>

    <h2>Main Responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Sending Requests:</strong> The client sends HTTP/HTTPS requests to the server to fetch or submit data.</li>
        <li><strong>Displaying Responses:</strong> After receiving a response from the server, the client processes and displays the data to the user.</li>
        <li><strong>Executing Local Code:</strong> Some clients can execute scripts locally (like JavaScript in a browser) to make the interface interactive.</li>
        <li><strong>Maintaining State:</strong> Clients may use cookies, sessions, or local storage to keep track of user data between requests.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <p>When you use a web browser to visit <code>www.example.com</code>:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>The browser (client) sends a <code>GET</code> request to the server hosting <code>example.com</code>.</li>
        <li>The server responds with an HTML page, CSS, JavaScript, and images.</li>
        <li>The client renders the page and allows you to interact with it.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Simplified HTTP Request from Client</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-http">
GET /index.html HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
User-Agent: Chrome/Edge/Firefox
Accept: text/html
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>This demonstrates how the client initiates communication and how the server responds, completing the client-server cycle.</p>

